The following debug line in DefaultConfluenceIndexManager.flushQueue() would really help index performance diagnosis:

                if(log.isDebugEnabled())    //Added by JL for patch
                   log.debug("Flushed " + stats.getQueueSize() + " items in " + stats.getElapsedMilliseconds() + " milliseconds");

The context is:
{code}
    public void flushQueue()
    {
        // if we are currently running a reindex, then we do not flush.
        if (isReIndexing())
        {
            return;
        }

        FlushStatistics currentFlushStats = new FlushStatistics();
        synchronized(lock)
        {
            // If we're currently flushing, wait for the existing flush to finish. We then flush again.
            //
            // If we were to just return, you'd break the contract of "the flush will be complete when this
            // method returns".
            //
            // If we were to just wait then return, you'd have situations where you added an item to the queue,
            // flushed, and that item wasn't processed because it was missed by the already-running flush.
            while (isFlushing())
            {
                try
                {
                    lock.wait();
                }
                catch (InterruptedException e)
                {
                    log.warn(this.toString() + " queue interrupted while waiting for previous flush to finish. " + e.getMessage());
                }
            }
            flushing = true;
            currentFlushStats.setStarted(new Date());
        }
        try
        {
            // retrieve the list of index task to be processed.
            List tasksToProcess = taskQueue.flushQueue();

            // TODO: start a new thread to handle the processing of the tasks. Note that we will need a way to force
            //       the flushing to be executed inline for the functional tests to behave correctly.


            if (tasksToProcess.size() > 0)
            {
                currentFlushStats.setQueueSize(tasksToProcess.size());
                currentFlushStats.setOptimised(false);
                currentFlushStats.setRecreated(false);
                processTasks(tasksToProcess, currentFlushStats);
                currentFlushStats.setFinished(new Date());
                stats = currentFlushStats;
                if(log.isDebugEnabled())    //Added by JL for patch
                   log.debug("Flushed " + stats.getQueueSize() + " items in " + stats.getElapsedMilliseconds() + " milliseconds");
{code}

This is from http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CONFKB/Index+Flush+Trigger+may+Consume+Resources - it'd be much better to just enable debugging rather than add this as a patch (which needs to be version specific).

